rue).newInstance();\n            } catch (Exception e) {\n                ;\n            }\n        if (fieldUtil == null)\n            fieldUtil = new FieldUtil14();\n    }\n\n    /**\n     * Returns an iterator for all fields for some class\n     *\n     * @param cls the class you are interested on\n     * @return an iterator for its fields\n     * @deprecated As of 1.3, use {@link #fieldsFor(Class)} instead\n     */\n    public Iterator serializableFieldsFor(final Class cls) {\n        return fieldsFor(cls);\n    }\n\n    /**\n     * Returns an iterator for all fields for some class\n     *\n     * @param cls the class you are interested on\n     * @return an iterator for its fields\n     */\n    public Iterator fieldsFor(final Class cls) {\n        return buildMap(cls, true).values().iterator();\n    }\n\n    /**\n     * Returns an specific field of some class. If definedIn is null, it searches for the field named 'name' inside the\n     * class cls. If definedIn is different than null, tries to find the specified field name in the specified class cls\n     * which should be defined in class definedIn (either equals cls or a one of it's superclasses)\n     *\n     * @param cls the class where the field is to be searched\n     * @param name the field name\n     * @param definedIn the superclass (or the class itself) of cls where the field was defined\n\n[143 more lines in file. Use offset=91 to continue.]"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1780843109077}}
[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Modifying test arrangements**\n\nI'm thinking about how to arrange tests together, but the order isn't guaranteed. I need to be cautious about existing tests triggering fast paths if I include a more restrictive one. The current setup creates a serializable type without a default constructor, which initializes nested reflections with a non-null method and doesn't allow fallback. So, should I adjust the test to cover either case? Maybe we could just remove the serializable fast path test altogether?\n\n**Evaluating test execution strategy**\n\nI'm thinking about how to avoid creating a second top-level file for the same active class. It seems like JUnit might fork per method, while Gradle's forkEvery option applies to test classes, not methods. Using a test suite could help launch subprocesses with different security managers, though that might complicate things with classloading and instrumentation. It’s clear that the security manager approach needs careful initialization, especially since the user reports only two remaining issues.\n\n**Evaluating coverage and build report**\n\nI'm looking to inspect the build report because it seems the current coverage file might not be updated. There hasn't been a run yet, so I might need to check the source regarding `Reflections.newInstance`. If a SecurityManager is present during setup, we might need a fallback. Should I consider setting a custom SecurityManager for a specific test? Also, I noticed that lines 117/120 are covered by existing tests. Adjusting to fallback could improve the coverage across all seven lines.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_045a421a425e7438016a25820b546081969be0b23bfca2a07e\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqJYJkJRiqvFU00DsQPmsCBdrQ6RFLryfDjMI_SRv-HQ5lMCR7KvJVRG1HB7_d_zOw-9ihA_1Rk7LFRuU7auY40yS7Z4Pp8Ce1XxdT6ue5_QtPyUeHrujuCV1tUkdh59S5YFHv-4QdawWX2nn4