[assistant] I investigated the remaining two call sites:
[assistant] 
[assistant] - `ObjectStreamClass.lookup(type)` at line 134
[assistant] - `ObjectInputStream.readObject()` at line 148
[assistant] 
[assistant] They are only reached in `PureJavaReflectionProvider.instantiateUsingSerialization(...)` when:
[assistant] 
[assistant] ```java
[assistant] if (Reflections.newInstance != null) {
[assistant]     ...
[assistant]     return Reflections.newInstance.invoke(osClass, new Object[0]);
[assistant] }
[assistant] ```
[assistant] 
[assistant] is skipped, meaning `PureJavaReflectionProvider.Reflections.newInstance` must be `null`.
[assistant] 
[assistant] For XStream `1.4.20` on the current JDK, that field becomes `null` only if XStream cannot make the private JDK method `ObjectStreamClass.newInstance()` accessible. The supported historical way to force that was a `SecurityManager` denying `ReflectPermission("suppressAccessChecks")`, but the current test JDK rejects `System.setSecurityManager(...)` with:
[assistant] 
[assistant] ```text
[assistant] UnsupportedOperationException: Setting a Security Manager is not supported
[assistant] ```
[assistant] 
[assistant] Removing `--add-opens` is not a supported alternative: it causes module-access failure during XStream’s internal static initialization rather than exercising the fallback path as normal library behavior.
[assistant] 
[assistant] So I left those two call sites uncovered rather than adding an unstable or unsupported test path. The failing `SecurityManager`-based fallback test has been removed/reverted, leaving only the supported `PureJavaReflectionProvider` coverage that already passed and covered the five reachable call sites.
